<section id="mission">

	<div class="container">

		<div class="intro">

			<header>

				<h2>Gaming Superpower</h2>

			</header>

			<p>
			Gaming on modern TV's has a lot of benefits, but there can be a lot of challenges to do so, especially with older consoles.  This website will try to help make gaming on
			modern displays easier, look better, and perform better - whether you are using a modern console or your childhood favorite retro console.
			</p>

			<p>
			There are a number of great resources on the web for modern and retro gaming, but it can take a lot of research to find out the best way to hook up an number of consoles,
			or how to make each look as good as possible.  We'll do our best to distill that information and give suggestions to provide the best experience for each, while referring
			to source material if you really want to get your hands dirty in the technical details.
			</p>

		</div>

	</div>

</section>

<section id="challenges">

	<div class="container">

		<div class="intro">

			<header>

				<h2>Challenges</h2>

			</header>

			<p>
			Gaming on modern TV's is quite a bit different than gaming on older LCD TV's, and presents a completely different set of challenges.
			We'll do our best to focus on each of the challenges and how it impacts each device you may use in your setup to allow you to achieve an optimal experience for your setup.
			</p>

		</div>

		<ul class="cards">

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/challenges/upscaling-zelda.jpg" alt="Poor Upscaling">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Poor Upscaling</h3>
						<p>Many modern TV's do a poor job upscaling retro games. The TV's are focused on video content scaling and do a poor job of scaling of 240p sources.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/challenges/input-lag.jpg" alt="Input Lag">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Input Lag</h3>
						<p>Modern TV's generally apply image processing to the input image that can cause lag. Some TV's do a better job than others or provide a game mode to reduce lag.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/challenges/connectivity.jpg" alt="Connectivity">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Connectivity</h3>
						<p>Most modern TV's only have HDMI ports, or potentially one or two older ports. If you plan to connect more than a few consoles you will run into issues, especially with retro consoles.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/challenges/no-signal.jpg" alt="Compatibility">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Compatibility</h3>
						<p>Many modern TV's simply aren't compatible with the signals produced by retro consoles. Finding either the right upscaler or TV can be a challenge.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

		</ul>

		<a class="button" href="/challenges">Learn more about challenges</a>

	</div>

</section>

<section id="upscalers">

	<div class="container">

		<div class="intro">

			<header>

				<h2>Upscalers</h2>

			</header>

			<p>

				Upscalers are a near-critical component of a modern retro gaming setup due to poor scaling on TV resolutions used by retro consoles.
				The two major options, the Open Source Scan Convertor (OSSC) and the XRGB-mini Framemeister, have tradeoffs depending on your setup, but we'll do our best to steer you in the right direction.

			</p>

		</div>

		<ul class="cards">

			<li>

				<figure id="ossc">
					<img src="~/images/devices/ossc-1.5a.jpg" alt="OSSC">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>OSSC</h3>
						<p>The Open Source Scan Converter (OSSC) provides a zero-lag solution, but has compromises on compatibility.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure id="xrgb-mini">
					<img src="~/images/devices/xrgb-mini_z01.jpg" alt="XRGB Mini Framemeister">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Framemeister</h3>
						<p>The XRGB Mini Framemeister is a more feature packed device with better compatibility, but at the cost of additional lag.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

		</ul>

		<a class="button" href="/upscalers">Learn more about upscalers</a>

	</div>

</section>

<section id="switches">

	<div class="container">

		<div class="intro">

			<header>

				<h2>Switches</h2>

			</header>

			<p>

				Once you have more than a few consoles you will quickly realize you need a way to switch between them without swapping cables.
				There are many types of switches, but the most common needs are for a SCART switches, component switches, and HDMI switches.

			</p>

		</div>

		<ul class="cards">

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/devices/gscartsw-3.4.jpg" alt="SCART Switches">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>SCART Switches</h3>
						<p>The Open Source Scan Converter (OSSC) provides a zero-lag solution, but has compromises on compatibility.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/devices/gcompsw-1.0.jpg" alt="Component Switches">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>Component Switches</h3>
						<p>The XRGB Mini Framemeister is a more feature packed device with better compatibility, but at the cost of additional lag.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

			<li>

				<figure>
					<img src="~/images/devices/hdmi-monoprice.jpg" alt="HDMI Switches">
					<figcaption>
						<h3>HDMI Switches</h3>
						<p>The XRGB Mini Framemeister is a more feature packed device with better compatibility, but at the cost of additional lag.</p>
					</figcaption>
				</figure>

			</li>

		</ul>

		<a class="button" href="/switches">Learn more about switches</a>

	</div>

</section>
